      "The village of Lower Slaughter, in which the manor sits, is part of the reason to stay here. Lower Slaughter is one of the most preserved villages in the Cotswolds, with a stream (the River Eye) running between the houses, a working nineteenth-century water mill, and a pedestrianised village centre that has been essentially unchanged since the Victorian period. It is smaller than Bourton-on-the-Water, which sits a mile to the south and receives the bulk of the region's tourist traffic, and consequently feels quieter. The manor house sits at one end of the village, on a side road with its own grounds.",
