      "The accommodation ranges across three registers: rooms in the original Rampsbeck house (traditional proportions, period-characterful), purpose-built rooms in the new wings added in 2017 (contemporary, larger, generally with better lake views), and alternative accommodation including shepherds huts in the grounds and a treehouse (fewer in number, particular character, popular for couples). The treehouse in particular books out months in advance.",
      "The Swim Club spa, built in 2017, is one of the more substantial hotel spas in the Lake District: a 20-metre indoor pool, hot tub, sauna, steam room, and treatment rooms. Because of the lakeshore location, the spa is designed to be used in combination with open-water swimming in the lake; many guests do both in a day.",
      "The Ashworth operating model at both Another Place and Watergate Bay specifically targets a market that traditional Lake District hotels have under-served: families with children who want luxury-level accommodation but also want genuinely child-friendly operation. Another Place has a dedicated children's club, child-specific menus, activity programming for children across school holidays, and outdoor equipment scaled for children as well as adults. This is a deliberate positioning against the general country-house hotel pattern of tolerating rather than catering to family guests.",
      "The three restaurants divide by register. Rampsbeck is the main formal restaurant in the original house. The Living Space is the all-day lounge dining room (breakfast, lunch, lighter evening food). The Glasshouse is the casual garden-terrace restaurant for warmer months. None are Michelin-starred but the cooking is consistent and focused on Cumbrian produce.",
      "Another Place, The Lake suits guests who want lakeshore access, active water-based activities, a contemporary family-friendly resort register, and a substantial spa. It does not suit anyone wanting traditional country-house aesthetics or an explicitly adults-only atmosphere; the property is unambiguous that children are welcomed rather than tolerated.",
