      "The Star Inn at Harome sits in a specific and rare British category: a pub-first rather than hotel-first operation, where the restaurant is the primary business and the rooms exist to allow guests to stay after a late dinner rather than drive. Chef Andrew Pern acquired the inn in 1996 and has developed it into one of the most-decorated village restaurants in the north of England. The 2021 fire and subsequent rebuild is itself a significant feature of the property's modern story; the fourteenth-century cruck frame and thatched roof were reconstructed using traditional methods, and the rebuilt inn retains the character of the original.",
      "Harome is a small North Yorkshire village of approximately 300 residents in the foothills of the North York Moors, five miles from the market town of Helmsley. The village itself is unusually compact and preserved, with a duck pond, an eleventh-century church (St Saviour's), and a small number of working farms. There is no commercial infrastructure beyond the Star Inn and two other small pubs. The location's quiet is structural rather than engineered; Harome is far enough from the main tourist routes to remain genuinely unvisited for most of the year.",
      "The cooking is what has made the property's reputation. Pern's register is modern British with strong Yorkshire produce emphasis: grouse in season, Yorkshire-reared beef and lamb, local cheeses, foraged elements from the surrounding moorland. The restaurant operates a main dining room in the original inn plus a separate more informal bar and snug service. Following the 2022 rebuild and 2024 Michelin reinstatement, the kitchen is arguably at its strongest point in the property's 28 years under Pern's ownership.",
